## Self-Review

**Assumptions made (not explicitly pinned down by the frozen spec, resolved here for implementability):**
- `toleranceOffset`, `proximityBand`, `stalenessBars`, and `reactionWindowBars` are all treated as **per-object, externally supplied policy values** set at submission time, rather than global parameters passed to `advance()`. The spec only explicitly named the reaction window as an external policy value; I extended the same ownership pattern (mechanism here, value supplied upstream) to the other three thresholds for consistency. This is an extension of an established principle, not a new one — flagging it for review in case the intended design wanted these as global/shared policy instead.
- Staleness is measured as `barIndex - formationBar`, not reset by an intervening Approach-then-revert cycle. The spec didn't specify whether approach should reset the staleness clock; I chose the simpler, deterministic interpretation.
- The "already breached at formation" retention case is given its own resolution constant (`PRE_RESOLVED_AT_FORMATION`) rather than being forced into Swept/Breached-Continuation/Invalidated-Stale, since fabricating one of those would violate the "no fabricated outcomes" principle. This constant is an implementation-level realization of the spec's retention policy, not a new architectural concept.
- `barstate.islast` is used as the trigger for `OUTCOME_UNDETERMINED`. This is deterministic per-run but worth double-checking in replay/backtest contexts to confirm it behaves as expected across your specific host script's bar-processing mode.

